</I><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR> <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/biggrin.gif">   Great !<BR>Not because of the final result but feeling the AI is working !<BR>I've only seen screenshots/read early reviews so far but I seems you guys are writing the kernel for human psychology in a robot  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/biggrin.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">lar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">&gt;&gt;Did you write custom editors for this ?<BR>                                Something like an imageviewer with a properties column ?&lt;&lt;<P>Yes, something like that  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"> Actually, the most of the editors are in-game, meaning that we can rapidly toggle between the game and the editor. The really advanced stuff is being done outside  <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/div.gif"> in a seperate window than the game window. Just try listing how much game objects need to be defined in a rpg, and how much properties these game objects have in order to figure out just how much editing work is necessary.<P>Lar<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tutamun</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Lar,<BR>do you want to discuss the interface here? I thought about it for a while...<P>*** *** *** *** ***<BR><I>Walking : Left click (walk to destination), Left drag (walk in direction)<BR>Running : Press R to toggle between walk/run or drag mouse to the edges of the screen<BR>Talking : Left click on friendly character<BR>Attacking: Left click on enemy character / hold ctrl to attack friendly character<BR>Using an object : Left click on it <BR>Moving an object : Left drag it<BR>Picking up an object in the inventory rag it on your character, interface bar, left click on it while holding the alt key<BR>Destroying an object:hold ctrl and click on object<BR>Casting a spell:Right click<BR>Using one object on another object : Drag one object on top of the other object</I><BR>*** *** *** *** ***<P>I don't think it will be very good the way you want to do it for a couple of reasons:<BR>1.) left click an object: uses it -and- (left click on enemy: attack -or- left click on ground: walk there)<BR>- In a (hectic) fight you may accidentaly click on a (poison) potion lying on the ground and use (drink) it.<BR>2.) left click an object: uses it -and- left drag an object: move it<BR>- By not holding the mouse button down long enough you will use the object instead of moving it.<BR>3.) (left drag an object: move it -or- left drag an object to character/interface-bar: pick it up) -and- left drag an object onto another object: use object on another object<BR>- Releasing the mouse button too early or too late results in the object being used on another object lying on the grond. What you wanted to do was pick it up or just move it.<BR>- You can not move one object on top of another because one is then used on the other.<BR>4.) left drag an object: move it -and- left drag on ground: walk in that direction<BR>- What happens when you hold the mouse over an object and keep pressing the left mouse button?<BR>- You should start walking in that direction (otherwise it would be hard to walk out of a fight when lots of stuff lies on the ground)<BR>- Now if you want to move the object but "forget" to move the mouse (or don't move it far enough) you will start walking there which is not what you wanted to do.<P>The problem is that objects get used and moved with the same mouse button. Even walking and attacking is done with this mouse button. This is very bad imho.<P>Diablo sold very well because it had a pretty good interface. They could have done a few things better, but why don't you stick to the basic Diablo interface and make it better suited for  <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/div.gif">? Diablo has the problem that you (try to) pick up something when left clicking on it. This is annoying during fights.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">lar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hi Tut,<P>&gt;&gt;The problem is that objects get used and moved with the same mouse button. Even walking and attacking is done with this mouse button. This is                           very bad imho.&lt;&lt;<P>So far the feedback has been pretty good actually with the described system. The line of reasoning you follow is the same we followed in the past, but for some reason, we didn't get that communicated to the player. This was the major problem. Then again, if there's one thing I learned about user interfaces, then it is that no matter how much you think about them, in the end it's only tests that give you the way it should be. Really, don't ask me why, but apparantly people want almost everything on the left mouse button. It's what they do intuitively.<P>Lar</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Deckard</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">People always have to get used to a new interface.  It's the use on the long run that counts.<BR>It's quite difficult to discuss such a thing since it's implementation can be very different (on the area of timing between clicks, position of the mouse, etc. .. .).<P>Maybe this interface suits  <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/div.gif"> 's game concept very good. IMHO it's easier to jugde after playing a beta.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tutamun</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hi Lar,<BR>here is what I have in mind. It's not perfect, but it tries to use your (current) controls to some extent and those of Diablo plus a bit more because of the need to combine objects and use spells on objects.<P>In Diablo you can only use objects that are in your inventory. To use them you right click on them. You can't cast a spell while the mouse pointer is over an object in the inventory. Doors can be opened/closed with the left click.<P>To avoid using -or- picking up objects during a fight they should not be used or picked up by left clicking on them. I would differ between objects that can't be used on their own, objects which can only be used once and objects which you can turn on and off.<P>Doors, windows, candles, torches, levers can be opened/closed, lighted/extinguished or pushed/pulled. Buttons can be pushed multiple times. (Some levers or buttons may be limited to using them once... but I still would put them in this category.) These should be used (togled on/off) by a left click.<BR>Food, potions can be used only once (eat/drink). Don't use it with a left click.<BR>Stones, Swords, Armor, etc. can't be used on their own. (If you want to use them you will need to equip them or use them on other objects.) You can't use them, so do nothing with them.<P>o left click on<BR>- ground: Walk there.<BR>- object: (Try to) walk there. Do as if you clicked on ground below object.<BR>+ ALT: Pick object up. (Or drop it if object is in the inventory.)<BR>+ CTRL: Destroy object.<BR>- toggle object: Activate/deactivate.<BR>+ ALT: Pick up if possible.<BR>+ CTRL: Destroy object. (Knock on door if weapon is put away -or- smash door if you have a weapon drawn.)<BR>- friend: Walk to him and talk. (Don't put weapon away if you have it drawn.)<BR>- enemy: Walk to him and attack. (Switch to attack mode.)<BR>- icon: Chooses the active spell/skill. (Casting is done with right click.)<P>o left drag<BR>- ground: Walk in that direction. (Run if mouse pointer is near screen border.)<BR>- object: Move object if you move (drag) the mouse, otherwise walk in that direction (only hold down left mouse button). Once the mouse pinter is off the initial object, you can move the mouse to change the direction you walk in.<BR>- object on object: Place object ontop of object.<BR>- object on character/inventory-bar: Pick object up if possible.<BR>- object on npc: Give object to npc. (If it's an enemy you could throw object (explosive potion). But maybe you should use right drag to throw.)<BR>- icon: Do nothing. You have clicked on the icon by accident and don't want anything to happen.<BR>+ CTRL, ALT or SHIFT?: Move icon on screen.<P>o right click on<BR>- ground: Only cast spell that dosn't need a target. (Not the best solution. see below *)<BR>- object lying on ground: Cast spell/use skill that affects object -or- cast spell that doesn't need a target (global spell/skill). This is how you use "pick lock".<BR>- object in inventory: Use object if you can use it on it's own.<BR>- npc: Cast spell/use skill that affect npc -or- global spells.<BR>- friend: Only spells where friend benefits.<BR>+ CTRL: You may harm friend. (eg. steal something from friendly npc.)<BR>- enemy: Only spells that harm enemy.<BR>- icon: Casts spell/uses skill on target. (You need this to cast spells on objects in your inventory, but it can also be used on npc's or objects in the world.)<P>o right drag<BR>- ground: ??? Draw a spell? Protective circle around you. Straight wall in front of you. (This could come into conflict with right drag object.)<BR>- object: Move a transparent image of the object (if you drop it, this image vanishes).<BR>- object on object: Use the first object on the second object.<BR>- object on character/inventory-bar: Use object directly from the ground. ie. drink potion.<BR>- object on friend: Tell him to <B>use</B> object (drink potion) and not only take it.<BR>- object on enemy: Throw object at enemy.<BR>- on npc: ??? Do nothing<BR>- icon: Do nothing. You have clicked on the icon by accident and don't want anything to happen.<P>o move mouse without holding a button pressed<BR>- CAPS-LOCK deactivated: Move mouse pointer. (wow!)<BR>+ SHIFT: Scroll screen when mouse pointer is at edge of screen. (Jumps back to character if SHIFT is released.)<BR>- CAPS-LOCK activated: Scroll screen when mouse pointer is at edge of screen. (Screen stays there until CAPS-LOCK is deactivated.)<BR>+ SHIFT: Screen jumps back to character.<P>*)<BR>This leaves a few special cases or problems:<BR>- "right click on object in inventory: Use object if you can use it on it's own." You can't cast a spell while the mouse pointer is over an object in your inventory. Thus you need to right click on the spell icon to activate the spell and then target the object. (The mouse pointer should change.)<BR>- When right clicking -and- a combat spell/skill is chosen, the nearest enemy should be targeted. This is to avoid not being able to cast a spell while mouse pointer is over object, ground or friend. (The same goes for nice spells on enemies.)<BR>- When right clicking -and- spell/skill that manipulates objects is chosen, the nearest object should be targeted. This is to avoid not being able to cast a spell while mouse pointer is over a npc or the ground.<P>What I like about this modified interface is:<BR>- You can use drag -or- click to walk without switching between modes. This is nice for players used to one (Diablo, BG) or the other (NOX).<BR>- You have very few conflicts while fighting or walking. (No picking up or using of objects.)<BR>- left mouse button only <B>moves</B>: walk, run, move objects, move weapon (attack - Okay, this one doesn't fit  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif">)<BR>- right mouse button only <B>uses</B>: cast spells, use skill, use object, combine objects<BR>- the most comon things (besides picking up objects) are easy to acomplish.<P>It is hard to pick up an item with this system. If a new player tries to pick up an item he will notice that left clicking on it will not do anything. After a few tries you could bring up a message box that says: "Try to pull the item to your character/inventory-bar -or- use ALT+left-click to pick up something." If he drags the object to the character a few times you could bring up a message box: "Using ALT+left-click also picks up something."<P>But as you said you need to test it. (And when I have time I will come and test it  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif">) But please also make sure that the interface is suited for hectic situations and avoids accidentaly doing the wrong thing easily. It is good if you learn the controls quickly/intuitive but they also have to be playable in the long run.<P>In the version I played it took me quite (too) long to learn the controls... but it was okay playing with them once I knew how to.<P>ps. Maybe only torches that are atached to a wall should be lighted/extinguished with a left click. Otherwise you light a torch that lies on the ground. Hmmm... don't know. But this would require more editing to be done and different behaviour for torches on the wall and ground... So it's probably not good.<p>[This message has been edited by Tutamun (edited 03-10-2000).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tutamun</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">What I said above (the problems with the current controls) only applies if you use the action click-click-click fighting. If you use the click once and watch the character do the fighting method, then you will have more time to position your mouse pointer and thus avoid "accidents". And then there is also the pause button when you don't want to make mistakes. If the interface is not perfect it won't matter that much for the calm players. But the action loving (why do we need a pause button?) players will have a hard time if the interface allows "accidents" to happen easily.<P>(I have just read it again... hope you understand it <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif">)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tutamun</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Oh! Did I mention that a good interface/controlls is very important?  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Deckard</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Lar,<P>How much is the actual build differing from his ideas ?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Nathan</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hi Lar,<P>Pressing ALT to highlight important items sounds like a nice idea, but how are you going to handle hidden items? ( a key under a barrel for example ). Do you take into account what the player can see on the screen?. It seems like a hard thing to do. </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">lar</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">&gt;&gt;Pressing ALT to highlight important items sounds like a nice idea, but how are you going to handle hidden items? ( a key under a barrel for<BR>                                example ). Do you take into account what the player can see on the screen?. It seems like a hard thing to do. &lt;&lt;<P>We can flag which objects show up, and which don't. <P>As for Tut's interface ideas. It's quite similar actually, except for the right mouse thing. We're trying to keep that one real simple in that it only does two things :<P>-Cast a spell<BR>-Close a plate<P><BR>Lar<BR> <P><BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Nathan</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">" We can flag which objects show up, and which don't. "<P>Oh  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/shame.gif"><P><BR> <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#282828"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ragon der Magier</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"><I>&gt;&gt;As for Tut's interface ideas. It's quite similar actually, except for the right mouse thing. We're trying to keep that one real simple in that it only does two things :<P>-Cast a spell<BR>-Close a plate&lt;&lt;</I><P>And that´s a big mistake IMHO!<P>Your using the mouse as your primary interface tool and can only take the minimum of two buttons into account.<BR>So w/ packing almost every possible option onto the left one and leave the other one to just spell casting and plate closing (what the heck are those "plates" btw?), seems very unbalanced and waste of potential in my eyes - as long as testing proves opposite.<BR>I mean, for Diablo it may be ok, but w/  <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/div.gif">´s sheer load of options?!?<BR>Left is overloaded and right underused.<P>Tut´s ideas appear much more reasonable to me, though:<BR>Dividing left=movement control and right=use options<BR> <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/icons/icon14.gif"> <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/icons/icon14.gif"> <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/icons/icon14.gif"> Tut!<P>What i dislike is the R key for running mode toggle:<BR>1. Any option that´s "hidden" in this messy letter key area is a pain<BR>2. Why not using the arrow up/down keys for ac-/deceleration? Or the +/- keys from the Numpad?<BR>3. What i miss is a third movement speed: where´s <I>sneaking mode</I>???<P>I agree that item pick up via left drag is a reasonable compromise. The benefit of avoiding interferences w/ fighting/movement issues counts more than a slight loss of convenience IMHO.<BR>The method isn´t so uncomfortable anyway as it is quite similar to the usual way files are put into the recycling bin for deletion under <I>Windows</I>.<P>Hotkey assignment: Why not via the &lt;shift&gt;+&lt;hotkey&gt; quite known i guess from <I>AoE</I>?<BR>The range is sufficient.<P>Pause game: Why is an icon obligate? Use the &lt;Pause&gt; key, what else anyway? <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P>Movement: "Left drag = walk in direction"<BR>Somehow i tend not to get this. Wouldn´t "Left drag = follow mouse" the more precise formulation?<BR>Maybe i´m just nitpicking... <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P>Strg: Using this as a "manual override" for performing unusual actions like item destruction is a clever and intuitive idea.  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/icons/icon14.gif"><P>drag object on enemies: i like your idea for throwing bombs, potions, stones etc. very much, Tut!  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/icons/icon14.gif"><BR>Lar: Make it so!  <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"><P><I>&gt;&gt;click on doors&lt;&lt;</I><BR>I thought doors open automatically when trying to walk through? (unless locked, then -&gt; right click=lockpick/use key <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif">)<P><I>&gt;&gt;combat mode toggling&lt;&lt;</I><BR>Hmm, didn´t you have a key for drawing/put back weapon? Why not linking this together?<BR>Would seem just logical to me...<P><I>&gt;&gt;under the barrel&lt;&lt;</I><BR>Well it should of course not be highlighted, as it´s only accessible after removing the barrel anyways.<P>Yours Ragon<P>P.S.: Thanx Lar btw for the insight into "the development of your development"! <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/wink.gif"> <IMG SRC="http://www.larian.com/ubb/biggrin.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#464646"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Tutamun</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial"> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR>Originally posted by lar:<BR><I>&gt;&gt;Pausing the game : There needs to be an icon<BR>Options : There needs to be an icon<BR>Lar</I><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>And you need icons for running/walking, switching to combat mode, scroll screen, ...<P>Everything that you need to activate/deactivate often, so that you don'T need to go through the options.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
